{"title_page": "David Fern\u00e1ndez (footballer, born 1976)", "text_new": "{{other people|David Fern\u00e1ndez}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2013}}\n{{spanish name|Fern\u00e1ndez|Miramontes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{infobox football biography\n| name = David Fern\u00e1ndez\n| image = Fernandez.jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt =\n| caption = Fern\u00e1ndez before a game with [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] in 2009\n| fullname = David Fern\u00e1ndez Miramontes\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1976|1|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[A Coru\u00f1a]], Spain]\n| height = 1.73 m\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = Liceo\n| youthyears2 = | youthclubs2 = Ural\n| youthyears3 = 1990\u20131994 | youthclubs3 = [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]]\n| years1 = 1994\u20131999 | clubs1 = [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a B|Deportivo B]] | caps1 = 70 | goals1 = 20\n| years2 = 1995\u20132000 | clubs2 = [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]] | caps2 = 42 | goals2 = 3\n| years3 = 1997\u20131998 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] (loan) | caps3 = 7 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 1999\u20132000 | clubs4 = \u2192 [[CD Toledo|Toledo]] (loan) | caps4 = 35 | goals4 = 7\n| years5 = 2000\u20132001 | clubs5 = [[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrie]] | caps5 = 20 | goals5 = 7\n| years6 = 2001\u20132002 | clubs6 = [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]] | caps6 = 41 | goals6 = 8\n| years7 = 2002\u20132005 | clubs7 = [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] | caps7 = 11 | goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 2003\u20132004 | clubs8 = \u2192 [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]] (loan) | caps8 = 27 | goals8 = 3\n| years9 = 2005\u20132006 | clubs9 = [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] | caps9 = 30 | goals9 = 5\n| years10 = 2006\u20132010 | clubs10 = [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] | caps10 = 82 | goals10 = 5\n| totalcaps = 365 | totalgoals = 58\n| club-update =\n}}\n'''David Fern\u00e1ndez Miramontes''' (born 20 January 1976) is a Spanish former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]], and a scout for English club [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].\n\nHe began his career with [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo]], but spent most of his career in [[Football in Scotland|Scottish football]]. He had a successful spell with [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]], which earned him a move to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Spain===\nBorn in [[A Coru\u00f1a]], [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]], Fern\u00e1ndez began his career with hometown club [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]]. In 1995, he helped [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a B|the reserves]] promote to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]], then was immediately promoted to the first team by manager [[John Toshack]], making his competitive debut in a [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]] [[1995\u201396 UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|tie]] against [[APOEL FC]] in Cyprus, on 14 September (0\u20130);<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1995/09/15/pagina-15/1313712/pdf.html|title=El Depor va a lo seguro y empata|trans-title=Depor play it safe and draw|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|last=Staramopoulos|first=Manos|language=Spanish|date=15 September 1995|accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref> his first [[La Liga]] appearance came on 26 November against [[Real Valladolid]], as he (again) came on as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Txiki Begiristain]] midway through the second half of the 3\u20131 home win.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.lavanguardia.com/preview/1995/11/27/pagina-21/33819275/pdf.html|title=Deportivo, 3 \u2013 Valladolid, 1|newspaper=[[La Vanguardia]]|language=Spanish|date=27 November 1995|accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nFern\u00e1ndez finished [[1995\u201396 La Liga|his first season]] with ''Depor'' with 26 official matches and four goals, three of those coming within less than one month: against [[Real Sociedad]] (1\u20131 home draw),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1996/02/19/pagina-24/1326410/pdf.html|title=La Real tampoco falia en Riazor|trans-title=Real also do not fail at Riazor|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|last=R\u00edos|first=Xoan|language=Spanish|date=19 February 1996|accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref> [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] (2\u20132, home)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1996/03/04/pagina-15/1329967/pdf.html|title=Otra pol\u00e9mica|trans-title=Another controversy|last=R\u00edos|first=Xoan|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|language=Spanish|date=4 March 1996|accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref> and [[Real Zaragoza]] (1\u20130 Cup Winners' Cup triumph).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1996/03/08/pagina-13/1337960/pdf.html|title=Decisivo David|trans-title=Decisive David|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|last=R\u00edos|first=Xoan|language=Spanish|date=8 March 1996|accessdate=22 March 2017}}</ref> He was eventually unable to break through to a regular starting place, being loaned twice to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] clubs, starting with [[Sevilla FC]] in the first part of [[1997\u201398 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1997\u201398]]; he spent the entire [[1999\u20132000 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1999\u20132000 campaign]] with [[CD Toledo]], appearing regularly but suffering team relegation, after which he was released by Deportivo.\n\n===Scotland===\nIn the 2000 off-season, former [[FC Barcelona]] and [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] player [[Steve Archibald]] was negotiating a deal to take control of [[Scottish Football League First Division|Scottish First Division]] side [[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrieonians]]. Using his contacts in Spain he enticed a number of players from there to try their luck in Scotland, with Fern\u00e1ndez among those accepting his offer.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/archibald-s-new-boys-share-latin-rhythm-at-dens-park-1-481869|title=Archibald's new boys share Latin rhythm at Dens Park|newspaper=[[The Scotsman]]|date=31 July 2000|accessdate=15 January 2015}}</ref> Due to financial problems relating to the takeover, the Spanish imports all had to be released in March 2001, but as one of those whose performances for Airdrie had impressed, he (along with teammate [[Javier S\u00e1nchez Broto]]) was signed up by another club in that level, [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]], who were on the verge of promotion to the [[Scottish Premier League|Premier League]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/spaniard-snapped-up-by-livingston-1-1287584|title=Spaniard snapped up by Livingston|newspaper=The Scotsman|date=1 April 2001|accessdate=15 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2001\u201302 Scottish Premier League|2001\u201302 season]], Fern\u00e1ndez featured prominently as the ''Livi Lions'' finished in third place and subsequently [[2002\u201303 UEFA Cup|qualified]] to the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]. His form prompted [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] manager [[Martin O'Neill]] to spend [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]1 million to sign the player for the [[Glasgow]] giants, on a four-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/scot_prem/2018354.stm|title=Celtic sign Fernandez|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=31 May 2002|accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nDespite this investment, however, Fern\u00e1ndez struggled to establish himself at Celtic, possibly because his thoughtful style of play did not fit in with the often direct approach of O'Neill's team. He scored his first and only goal for the team against [[FK S\u016bduva Marijampol\u0117]] in the [[2002\u201303 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]], on 3 October 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/uefa_cup/2291685.stm|title=Celtic stroll into second round|publisher=BBC Sport|date=3 October 2002|accessdate=17 January 2010}}</ref> After a [[2002\u201303 Scottish Premier League|first season]] spent almost exclusively on the bench,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/scot_prem/3167969.stm|title=Fernandez fears for future|publisher=BBC Sport|date=20 August 2003|accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref> his future looked to lie away from Celtic, and he was loaned back to Livingston for [[2003\u201304 Scottish Premier League|2003\u201304]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/3193499.stm|title=Fernandez back at Livi|publisher=BBC Sport|date=30 August 2003|accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref> where he was part of the side that [[2004 Scottish League Cup Final|won]] the [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]] after beating [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] 2\u20130.<ref name=\"Livi\"/>\n\nUpon his return to [[Celtic Park]], Fern\u00e1ndez was confined to [[reserve team]] football and, in August 2005, he was released from his link but remained in Scotland, signing a three-year deal with [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/4146874.stm|title=Fernandez moves on to Tannadice|publisher=BBC Sport|date=12 August 2005|accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref> However, in April 2006, following a change in management at the club, he was informed by new manager [[Craig Brewster]] that he would be allowed to leave the club at the end of [[2005\u201306 Scottish Premier League|the season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/d/dundee_utd/4897128.stm|title=Tannadice trio told to leave club|publisher=BBC Sport|date=10 April 2006|accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 August 2006, Fern\u00e1ndez agreed a severance package with United and promptly signed a two-year contract with [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/k/kilmarnock/4786729.stm|title=Kilmarnock wrap up Fernandez deal|publisher=BBC Sport|date=18 August 2006|accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref> On 29 October, after a mistimed tackled by Celtic [[Defender (association football)|defender]] [[Gary Caldwell]], he suffered a serious [[cruciate ligament]] injury, going on to miss the remainder of [[2006\u201307 Scottish Premier League|the campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/k/kilmarnock/6096976.stm|title=Fernandez is facing 10 months out|publisher=BBC Sport|date=30 October 2006|accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nFern\u00e1ndez was released by Kilmarnock when his contract expired in May 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/scottish-premier/kilmarnock/180014-fernandez-considers-quitting-football-after-kilmarnock-exit/|title=Fernandez considers quitting football after Kilmarnock exit|publisher=[[STV News]]|date=27 May 2010|accessdate=29 July 2010}}</ref> The 34-year-old subsequently returned to A Coru\u00f1a, training with amateurs Silva SD to keep fit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.laopinioncoruna.es/deportes/2010/08/13/ex-deportivista-david-fernandez-ejercita-silva/410308.html|title=El ex deportivista David Fern\u00e1ndez se ejercita con el Silva|trans-title=Former Deportivo player David Fern\u00e1ndez trains with Silva|newspaper=La Opini\u00f3n A Coru\u00f1a|last=Garc\u00eda|first=David|language=Spanish|date=13 August 2010|accessdate=3 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Post-retirement==\nIn summer 2012, Fern\u00e1ndez was appointed [[Scout (sport)|scout]] at [[Premier League]] side [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenational.ae/sport/football/mancini-still-keen-to-get-de-rossi-at-manchester-city|title=Mancini still keen to get De Rossi at Manchester City|newspaper=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]|last=Castles|first=Duncan|date=4 August 2012|accessdate=3 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Deportivo'''\n*[[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]]: [[1995 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|1995]]\n\n'''Airdrieonians'''\n*[[Scottish Challenge Cup]]: [[2000\u201301 Scottish Challenge Cup|2000\u201301]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/1031544.stm|title=Airdrie lift Challenge Cup|publisher=BBC Sport|date=19 November 2000|accessdate=15 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''Celtic'''\n*[[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]: Runner-up [[2002\u201303 UEFA Cup|2002\u201303]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/3043029.stm|title=Porto end Celtic's UEFA dream|publisher=BBC Sport|date=21 May 2003|accessdate=15 January 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Scottish League Cup]]: Runner-up [[2002\u201303 Scottish League Cup|2002\u201303]]\n\n'''Livingston'''\n*[[Scottish League Cup]]: [[2003\u201304 Scottish League Cup|2003\u201304]]<ref name=\"Livi\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_div_1/3502960.stm|title=Livingston lift CIS Cup|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 March 2004|accessdate=15 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''Kilmarnock'''\n*[[Scottish League Cup]]: Runner-up [[2006\u201307 Scottish League Cup|2006\u201307]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|528}}\n*[http://deportivo-la-coruna.com/profiles/pastplayers/david-fernandez.html Deportivo archives]\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fernandez, David}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from A Coru\u00f1a]]\n[[Category:Galician sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Galician footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Deportivo Fabril players]]\n[[Category:Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a players]]\n[[Category:Sevilla FC players]]\n[[Category:CD Toledo players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Airdrieonians F.C. (1878) players]]\n[[Category:Livingston F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Celtic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dundee United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Kilmarnock F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people|David Fern\u00e1ndez}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2013}}\n{{spanish name|Fern\u00e1ndez|Miramontes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{infobox football biography\n| name = David Fern\u00e1ndez\n| image = Fernandez.jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt =\n| caption = Fern\u00e1ndez before a game with [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] in 2009\n| fullname = David Fern\u00e1ndez Miramontes\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1976|1|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[A Coru\u00f1a]], [[Spain]] \n| height = {{height|m=1.73}}\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = Liceo\n| youthyears2 = | youthclubs2 = Ural\n| youthyears3 = 1990\u20131994 | youthclubs3 = [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]]\n| years1 = 1994\u20131999 | clubs1 = [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a B|Deportivo B]] | caps1 = 70 | goals1 = 20\n| years2 = 1995\u20132000 | clubs2 = [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]] | caps2 = 42 | goals2 = 3\n| years3 = 1997\u20131998 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] (loan) | caps3 = 7 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 1999\u20132000 | clubs4 = \u2192 [[CD Toledo|Toledo]] (loan) | caps4 = 35 | goals4 = 7\n| years5 = 2000\u20132001 | clubs5 = [[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrie]] | caps5 = 20 | goals5 = 7\n| years6 = 2001\u20132002 | clubs6 = [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]] | caps6 = 41 | goals6 = 8\n| years7 = 2002\u20132005 | clubs7 = [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] | caps7 = 11 | goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 2003\u20132004 | clubs8 = \u2192 [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]] (loan) | caps8 = 27 | goals8 = 3\n| years9 = 2005\u20132006 | clubs9 = [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] | caps9 = 30 | goals9 = 5\n| years10 = 2006\u20132010 | clubs10 = [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] | caps10 = 82 | goals10 = 5\n| totalcaps = 365 | totalgoals = 58\n| club-update =\n}}\n'''David Fern\u00e1ndez Miramontes''' (born 20 January 1976) is a Spanish retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]], and a scout for English club [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].\n\nHe began his career with [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo]], but spent most of his career in [[Football in Scotland|Scottish football]]. He had a successful spell with [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]], which earned him a move to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Spain===\nBorn in [[A Coru\u00f1a]], [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]], Fern\u00e1ndez began his career with hometown club [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]]. In 1995, he helped [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a B|the reserves]] promote to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]], then was immediately promoted to the first team by manager [[John Toshack]], making his competitive debut in a [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]] [[1995\u201396 UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|tie]] against [[APOEL FC]] in Cyprus, on 14 September (0\u20130);<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1995/09/15/pagina-15/1313712/pdf.html|title=El Depor va a lo seguro y empata|trans-title=Depor play it safe and draw|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|last=Staramopoulos|first=Manos|language=Spanish|date=15 September 1995|accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref> his first [[La Liga]] appearance came on 26 November against [[Real Valladolid]], as he (again) came on as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Txiki Begiristain]] midway through the second half of the 3\u20131 home win.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.lavanguardia.com/preview/1995/11/27/pagina-21/33819275/pdf.html|title=Deportivo, 3 \u2013 Valladolid, 1|newspaper=[[La Vanguardia]]|language=Spanish|date=27 November 1995|accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nFern\u00e1ndez finished [[1995\u201396 La Liga|his first season]] with ''Depor'' with 26 official matches and four goals, three of those coming within less than one month: against [[Real Sociedad]] (1\u20131 home draw),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1996/02/19/pagina-24/1326410/pdf.html|title=La Real tampoco falia en Riazor|trans-title=Real also do not fail at Riazor|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|last=R\u00edos|first=Xoan|language=Spanish|date=19 February 1996|accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref> [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] (2\u20132, home)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1996/03/04/pagina-15/1329967/pdf.html|title=Otra pol\u00e9mica|trans-title=Another controversy|last=R\u00edos|first=Xoan|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|language=Spanish|date=4 March 1996|accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref> and [[Real Zaragoza]] (1\u20130 Cup Winners' Cup triumph).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1996/03/08/pagina-13/1337960/pdf.html|title=Decisivo David|trans-title=Decisive David|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|last=R\u00edos|first=Xoan|language=Spanish|date=8 March 1996|accessdate=22 March 2017}}</ref> He was eventually unable to break through to a regular starting place, being loaned twice to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] clubs, starting with [[Sevilla FC]] in the first part of [[1997\u201398 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1997\u201398]]; he spent the entire [[1999\u20132000 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1999\u20132000 campaign]] with [[CD Toledo]], appearing regularly but suffering team relegation, after which he was released by Deportivo.\n\n===Scotland===\nIn the 2000 off-season, former [[FC Barcelona]] and [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] player [[Steve Archibald]] was negotiating a deal to take control of [[Scottish Football League First Division|Scottish First Division]] side [[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrieonians]]. Using his contacts in Spain he enticed a number of players from there to try their luck in Scotland, with Fern\u00e1ndez among those accepting his offer.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/archibald-s-new-boys-share-latin-rhythm-at-dens-park-1-481869|title=Archibald's new boys share Latin rhythm at Dens Park|newspaper=[[The Scotsman]]|date=31 July 2000|accessdate=15 January 2015}}</ref> Due to financial problems relating to the takeover, the Spanish imports all had to be released in March 2001, but as one of those whose performances for Airdrie had impressed, he (along with teammate [[Javier S\u00e1nchez Broto]]) was signed up by another club in that level, [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]], who were on the verge of promotion to the [[Scottish Premier League|Premier League]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/spaniard-snapped-up-by-livingston-1-1287584|title=Spaniard snapped up by Livingston|newspaper=The Scotsman|date=1 April 2001|accessdate=15 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2001\u201302 Scottish Premier League|2001\u201302 season]], Fern\u00e1ndez featured prominently as the ''Livi Lions'' finished in third place and subsequently [[2002\u201303 UEFA Cup|qualified]] to the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]. His form prompted [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] manager [[Martin O'Neill]] to spend [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]1 million to sign the player for the [[Glasgow]] giants, on a four-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/scot_prem/2018354.stm|title=Celtic sign Fernandez|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=31 May 2002|accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nDespite this investment, however, Fern\u00e1ndez struggled to establish himself at Celtic, possibly because his thoughtful style of play did not fit in with the often direct approach of O'Neill's team. He scored his first and only goal for the team against [[FK S\u016bduva Marijampol\u0117]] in the [[2002\u201303 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]], on 3 October 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/uefa_cup/2291685.stm|title=Celtic stroll into second round|publisher=BBC Sport|date=3 October 2002|accessdate=17 January 2010}}</ref> After a [[2002\u201303 Scottish Premier League|first season]] spent almost exclusively on the bench,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/scot_prem/3167969.stm|title=Fernandez fears for future|publisher=BBC Sport|date=20 August 2003|accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref> his future looked to lie away from Celtic, and he was loaned back to Livingston for [[2003\u201304 Scottish Premier League|2003\u201304]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/3193499.stm|title=Fernandez back at Livi|publisher=BBC Sport|date=30 August 2003|accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref> where he was part of the side that [[2004 Scottish League Cup Final|won]] the [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]] after beating [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] 2\u20130.<ref name=\"Livi\"/>\n\nUpon his return to [[Celtic Park]], Fern\u00e1ndez was confined to [[reserve team]] football and, in August 2005, he was released from his link but remained in Scotland, signing a three-year deal with [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/4146874.stm|title=Fernandez moves on to Tannadice|publisher=BBC Sport|date=12 August 2005|accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref> However, in April 2006, following a change in management at the club, he was informed by new manager [[Craig Brewster]] that he would be allowed to leave the club at the end of [[2005\u201306 Scottish Premier League|the season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/d/dundee_utd/4897128.stm|title=Tannadice trio told to leave club|publisher=BBC Sport|date=10 April 2006|accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 August 2006, Fern\u00e1ndez agreed a severance package with United and promptly signed a two-year contract with [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/k/kilmarnock/4786729.stm|title=Kilmarnock wrap up Fernandez deal|publisher=BBC Sport|date=18 August 2006|accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref> On 29 October, after a mistimed tackled by Celtic [[Defender (association football)|defender]] [[Gary Caldwell]], he suffered a serious [[cruciate ligament]] injury, going on to miss the remainder of [[2006\u201307 Scottish Premier League|the campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/k/kilmarnock/6096976.stm|title=Fernandez is facing 10 months out|publisher=BBC Sport|date=30 October 2006|accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nFern\u00e1ndez was released by Kilmarnock when his contract expired in May 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/scottish-premier/kilmarnock/180014-fernandez-considers-quitting-football-after-kilmarnock-exit/|title=Fernandez considers quitting football after Kilmarnock exit|publisher=[[STV News]]|date=27 May 2010|accessdate=29 July 2010}}</ref> The 34-year-old subsequently returned to A Coru\u00f1a, training with amateurs Silva SD to keep fit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.laopinioncoruna.es/deportes/2010/08/13/ex-deportivista-david-fernandez-ejercita-silva/410308.html|title=El ex deportivista David Fern\u00e1ndez se ejercita con el Silva|trans-title=Former Deportivo player David Fern\u00e1ndez trains with Silva|newspaper=La Opini\u00f3n A Coru\u00f1a|last=Garc\u00eda|first=David|language=Spanish|date=13 August 2010|accessdate=3 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Post-retirement==\nIn summer 2012, Fern\u00e1ndez was appointed [[Scout (sport)|scout]] at [[Premier League]] side [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenational.ae/sport/football/mancini-still-keen-to-get-de-rossi-at-manchester-city|title=Mancini still keen to get De Rossi at Manchester City|newspaper=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]|last=Castles|first=Duncan|date=4 August 2012|accessdate=3 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Deportivo'''\n*[[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]]: [[1995 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|1995]]\n\n'''Airdrieonians'''\n*[[Scottish Challenge Cup]]: [[2000\u201301 Scottish Challenge Cup|2000\u201301]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/1031544.stm|title=Airdrie lift Challenge Cup|publisher=BBC Sport|date=19 November 2000|accessdate=15 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''Celtic'''\n*[[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]: Runner-up [[2002\u201303 UEFA Cup|2002\u201303]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/3043029.stm|title=Porto end Celtic's UEFA dream|publisher=BBC Sport|date=21 May 2003|accessdate=15 January 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Scottish League Cup]]: Runner-up [[2002\u201303 Scottish League Cup|2002\u201303]]\n\n'''Livingston'''\n*[[Scottish League Cup]]: [[2003\u201304 Scottish League Cup|2003\u201304]]<ref name=\"Livi\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_div_1/3502960.stm|title=Livingston lift CIS Cup|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 March 2004|accessdate=15 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''Kilmarnock'''\n*[[Scottish League Cup]]: Runner-up [[2006\u201307 Scottish League Cup|2006\u201307]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|528}}\n*[http://deportivo-la-coruna.com/profiles/pastplayers/david-fernandez.html Deportivo archives]\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fernandez, David}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from A Coru\u00f1a]]\n[[Category:Galician sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Galician footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Deportivo Fabril players]]\n[[Category:Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a players]]\n[[Category:Sevilla FC players]]\n[[Category:CD Toledo players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Airdrieonians F.C. (1878) players]]\n[[Category:Livingston F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Celtic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dundee United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Kilmarnock F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor corrections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Fern%C3%A1ndez_(footballer,_born_1976)"}
